The way to approach this problem in the least amount of time is to first find the eigenvalues and corresponding eigenvectors. This will reduce the problem to powers of diagonalizable matrices which happen to be very easy to compute.</think> <answer><pre>The eigenvalues turn out to be $1$ and $1$, so they commute. Note that $A^n$ is just $A$ multiplied together $n$ times, so $A^{31} = A$ and $A^{40} = A^2$. Then we can compute
\begin{align*}
  \mathbf{A}^2 &= \mathbf{A} \mathbf{A} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 & 7 \\ -1 & -2 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 3 & 7 \\ -1 & -2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ -1 & -1 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}
Now note that $1$ is its own eigenvalue, so repeatedly multiplying $A$ gives
\[\mathbf{A}^{27} + \mathbf{A}^{31} + \mathbf{A}^{40} = \mathbf{A} + \mathbf{A} + \mathbf{A}^2 = \boxed{\mathbf{A}^2 + 2 \mathbf{A}} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 6 & 9 \\ -2 & -1 \end{pmatrix}}.\]</answer>

